Here is the demonstration of formatting a header and a list in markdown:

**Markdown:**

* Header 1
  - List item 1
  - List item 2

**Formatted Output (HTML):**

<h1>Header 1</h1>
<ul>
  <li>List item 1</li>
  <li>List item 2</li>
</ul>

Now, here is the C++ function that takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing html formatted text:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <boost/algorithm/string.hpp>
#include <boost/regex.hpp>

std::string formatMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
  std::string html;

  // Remove any leading or trailing spaces
  boost::algorithm::trim(markdown);

  // Check if the input is empty
  if (markdown.empty()) {
    return html;
  }

  // Parse the markdown into a tree of tokens
  boost::regex re("^(\\s*#\\s*|\\s*\\-\\s*|\\s*\\*\\s*|\\s*\\+\\s*|\\s*\\=\\s*|\\s*\\{\\s*|\\s*\\}\\s*|\\s*\\[\\s*|\\s*\\]\\s*|\\s*\\(\\s*|\\s*\\)\\s*|\\s*\\d+\\s*|\\s*\"[^\"]*\"\\s*|\\s*[^\\s#\\-\\*\\+\\=\\{\\}\\[\\]\\(\\)\\d\"]*");
  boost::smatch matches;
  std::vector<std::string> tokens;
  while (boost::regex_search(markdown, matches, re)) {
    tokens.push_back(matches.str());
  }

  // Iterate through the tokens and generate the HTML output
  for (const auto& token : tokens) {
    if (token == "#") {
      html += "<h1>";
    } else if (token == "-") {
      html += "<ul>";
    } else if (token == "*") {
      html += "<li>";
    } else if (token == "+") {
      html += "<li>";
    } else if (token == "=") {
      html += "<li>";
    } else if (token == "{") {
      html += "<blockquote>";
    } else if (token == "}") {
      html += "</blockquote>";
    } else if (token == "[") {
      html += "<ul>";
    } else if (token == "]") {
      html += "</ul>";
    } else if (token == "(") {
      html += "<dl>";
    } else if (token == ")") {
      html += "</dl>";
    } else if (boost::regex_match(token, boost::regex("\\d+"))) {
      html += "<li>" + token + "</li>";
    } else if (boost::regex_match(token, boost::regex("\"[^\"]*\""))) {
      html += "<li>" + token + "</li>";
    } else {
      html += token;
    }
  }

  return html;
}
```

Here's a sample code snippet that shows how to implement the snake's movement using images in C:

**Snake Movement using Images in C:**

**Header File:**

#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <conio.h>
#include <graphics.h>

#define SNAKE_WIDTH 10
#define SNAKE_HEIGHT 10

**Global Variables:**

int snakeX[SNAKE_WIDTH], snakeY[SNAKE_HEIGHT];
int snakeDirection = 0; // 0 = up, 1 = right, 2 = down, 3 = left

**Function Prototypes:**

void drawSnake();
void moveSnake();

**Main Function:**

int main() {
    int x, y, i;
    initgraph(640, 480, "c:\\turbografx\\bgi");

    for (i = 0; i < SNAKE_WIDTH; i++) {
        snakeX[i] = 320 - (i * 10);
        snakeY[i] = 240;
    }

    while (1) {
        drawSnake();
        moveSnake();
        delay(100);
    }

    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

**Draw Snake Function:**

void drawSnake() {
    int i;
    for (i = 0; i < SNAKE_WIDTH; i++) {
        putimage(snakeX[i], snakeY[i], (char *) "snake.gif", 0);
    }
}

**Move Snake Function:**

void moveSnake() {
    int i, j;
    for (i = SNAKE_WIDTH - 1; i > 0; i--) {
        snakeX[i] = snakeX[i - 1];
        snakeY[i] = snakeY[i - 1];
    }

    switch (snakeDirection) {
        case 0: // up
            snakeY[0] -= 10;
            break;
        case 1: // right
            snakeX[0] += 10;
            break;
        case 2: // down
            snakeY[0] += 10;
            break;
        case 3: // left
            snakeX[0] -= 10;
            break;
    }

    drawSnake();
}

**Explanation:**

In this code, we define the snake's width and height as global variables. We also define an array to store the x and y coordinates of each segment of the snake.

The main function initializes the graphics system and sets up the snake's initial position. The while loop continuously draws the snake and moves it according to the direction specified.

The drawSnake function simply draws the snake using the putimage function, which takes the x and y coordinates of the top-left corner of the image, and the image to be drawn.

The moveSnake function moves each segment of the snake to its new position based on the direction specified. It then calls the drawSnake function to redraw the snake in its new position.

Note: You need to have the snake.gif image in the same directory as the executable file to run this code.

